ti-token, so they lift confidence via the direct\n109:   // lane without firing on single tokens like \"scan\"/\"profile\"/\"search\"/\"cms\").\n110:   'webflow cms': [['mcp-code-mode', 1.5], ['sk-code', -0.5]],\n111:   'cms collection': [['mcp-code-mode', 1.4]],\n112:   'structural search': [['system-code-graph', 1.5]],\n113:   'code graph search': [['system-code-graph', 1.5]],\n114:   'find code that': [['system-code-graph', 1.4]],\n115:   'code that handles': [['system-code-graph', 1.4]],\n116:   '5d scoring': [['deep-agent-improvement', 1.5]],\n117:   '5-dimension agent scoring': [['deep-agent-improvement', 1.6]],\n118:   'integration scan': [['deep-agent-improvement', 1.5]],\n119:   'dynamic profile': [['deep-agent-improvement', 1.5]],\n120:   // Lane B (model-benchmark) command anchors. These benchmark or optimize a\n121:   // model / prompt framework against fixtures, routed by the\n122:   // /deep:start-model-benchmark-loop command (canonical deep-model-benchmark).\n123:   // Lane B runs as a MODE of the deep-agent-improvement skill. The projection\n124:   // exposes a single canonical node for that skill (deep-agent-improvement),\n125:   // so the disambiguation penalty must target that canonical id to actually\n126:   // lower the ranked Lane A candidate. The earlier alias-shaped target\n127:   // (command-spec-kit-deep-agent-improvement) is not a projection node, so it\n128:   // never reached the ranked skill and the penalty was inert. The bounded\n129:   // penalty keeps benchmark phrasing from out-ranking deep-model-benchmark.\n130:   'benchmark a model': [['deep-model-benchmark', 1.6], ['deep-agent-improvement', -0.6]],\n131:   'benchmark a prompt framework': [['deep-model-benchmark', 1.6], ['deep-agent-improvement', -0.6]],\n132:   'benchmark a prompt': [['deep-model-benchmark', 1.4], ['deep-agent-improvement', -0.4]],\n133:   'optimize a model': [['deep-model-benchmark', 1.5], ['deep-agent-improvement', -0.6]],\n134:   'optimize a prompt framework':